    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Lines of closely spaced hedges typically interspersed with trees, usually planted on a low earthen wall or base and trained to form a barrier or mark the boundary of an area, particularly in fields or between properties.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000078864/Arnold, Influence of Ditch and Hedgerow Structure (1983)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000078863/Baudry et al, Hedgerows: International Perspective on their Origin (2000)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Rijen heggen met weinig tussenruimte, vaak met bomen ertussen, meestal geplant op een lage aarden wal of grond en zodanig geleid dat ze een barrière vormen of de grens van een gebied markeren, in het bijzonder op velden of tussen percelen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
